  <detection>
    - Monitor registry for tag overwrites
    - Alert on unsigned image deployments
    - Track base image changes
    - Scan images for known vulnerabilities
    - Compare image digests across deployments
  </detection>

  <validation>
    - Successfully push modified image
    - Overwrite existing image tags
    - Inject malicious layer
    - Bypass image signing verification
    - Extract secrets from image history
  </validation>

  <pro_tips>
    - docker history shows all layers, including "deleted" content
    - Image digests in Kubernetes deployments prevent tag poisoning
    - Harbor and ECR support immutable tags - check if enabled
    - Multi-stage builds can leak secrets in builder stage
    - cosign keyless signing uses OIDC - check trust policies
    - Registry webhooks can alert on pushes - check configuration
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>Container images are immutable but tags are not. Anyone with push access can replace "latest" or any other tag with a malicious image. Use digests for critical deployments, enable image signing, and monitor registry activity. Image poisoning scales instantly - every new container gets the malicious version.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
